<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-836-074  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 836 074.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 10 1990 v24 n37 p51(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japanese take long-term view of OS/2.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Valigra, Lori.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>OS/2 has yet to become a standard operating system formicrocomputers in Japan and estimates of its future acceptancevary greatly.andP;  The Japan Electronic Industry DevelopmentAssociation estimates that 1.7 million of the 2.8 millionmicrocomputers expected to be sold in 1993 will be 32-bitmachines.andP;  This causes some analysts to expect that 60 percent ofthe machines sold in 1993 will be OS/2-based, while other analystsput the figure closer to 20 or 30 percent.andP;  OS/2's multitaskingand networking functions makes it attractive but another keyfactor that will make the operating system acceptable in thefuture is whether the graphic applications will proliferate andwhether programmers will be able to stay up with the more fullydeveloped features of the operating system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanOperating SystemsOS-2MultitaskingTrendsFuture of Computing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>